  "prompt": "What should I do if I lost my Chase debit card?",
  "response": "If you've lost your Chase debit card, here's a step-by-step guide on what you should do immediately:\n\n**1. Freeze Your Card Immediately (The Most Important Step):**\n\n*   **Chase Mobile App:** This is usually the fastest method.\n    *   Log in to your Chase Mobile app.\n    *   Find your debit card details.\n    *   Look for an option to \"Lock\" or \"Freeze\" your card.  Use that.  This *temporarily* blocks new purchases or ATM withdrawals.\n\n*   **Chase Website:** If you can't use the app, use the website.\n    *   Log in to your Chase account on the Chase website.\n    *   Find your debit card details.\n    *   Look for an option to \"Lock\" or \"Freeze\" your card.\n\n*   **Call Chase Customer Service (If the App/Website Isn't Working):**  Call them immediately. This should be your next step if you can't access the app or website.\n    *   Call the number on the Chase website or the back of your credit card (if you have one handy).  The general customer service number is: **1-800-935-9935**\n    *   Tell them you need to report a lost or stolen debit card.\n\n**Why freezing is so important:** Freezing stops potential fraudulent use of your card while you look for it.  If you find it, you can simply unfreeze it. If not, you've already taken the most critical step to protect yourself.\n\n**2. Review Recent Transactions:**\n\n*   Once you've frozen your card, carefully review your recent transactions in the Chase app or on the website. Look for any unauthorized or suspicious activity.\n\n**3. Report the Loss/Theft and Request a New Card:**\n\n*   **After freezing your card and checking for fraud, you need to report it as lost/stolen to Chase and request a replacement.** You can usually do this through the app, website, or during the phone call you make to customer service.\n*   Be prepared to answer security questions to verify your identity.\n*   Confirm your mailing address for the new card.\n*   Ask about expedited shipping if you need the card quickly.\n\n**4. File a Police Report (Optional but Recommended, Especially if Stolen):**\n\n*   If you believe your card was stolen, or if you see fraudulent activity on your account, filing a police report is a good idea. It can help with your claim if you need to dispute any charges.\n*   Keep a copy of the police report for your records.\n\n**5. Update Automatic Payments:**\n\n*   Once you receive your new debit card, update any automatic payments (subscriptions, bills, etc.) that are linked to your old card.  This is crucial to avoid service interruptions.\n\n**6. Consider Changing Your PIN:**\n\n*   If you think your PIN might have been compromised, change it as soon as you receive your new card. You can usually do this at a Chase ATM or by calling Chase customer service.\n\n**Important Considerations and Tips:**\n\n*   **Act Fast:** Time is of the essence. The quicker you report the loss, the less liability you'll have for fraudulent charges.\n*   **Chase's Zero Liability Policy:** Chase has a zero liability policy for unauthorized transactions, but you must report the loss promptly.\n*   **Keep Chase's Contact Information Handy:** Store the Chase customer service number in your phone and/or in a safe place at home.\n*   **Monitor Your Account Regularly:** Even after you get your new card, continue to monitor your account statements for any suspicious activity.\n*   **Fraudulent Charges:** If you find fraudulent charges, dispute them with Chase immediately. They will investigate and typically credit your account if the charges are confirmed to be fraudulent.\n\nBy following these steps, you can minimize the risk of financial loss and protect your account after losing your Chase debit card.\n",
